3fbc6a92087a,How would one learn how to code who has no experience?,"There are a few ways to learn how to code without any prior experience:

1. Online courses: There are many online courses that teach coding for beginners, such as Codecademy, Codingphil, and FreeCodeCamp. These courses often have interactive lessons and exercises that make coding more accessible.

2. Books: There are also many books on computer programming, such as ""Designing Computer Programs"" by Erica Sadun, ""Python Crash Course"" by Eric Matthes, and ""Coding Essentials"" by Mozilla Developer Network.

3. YouTube tutorials: YouTube has many great tutorials that teach coding concepts in an easy-to-understand manner. Some popular channels include Practical Python and Coding, and Codecademy.

4. Community development programs: Many organizations and organizations run community development programs that offer coding classes and workshops for beginners. These programs often include a curriculum, mentorship, and opportunities for hands-on coding.

5. Books and podcasts: There are many books and podcasts that teach coding concepts in a way that is easy to understand. Examples include ""Coding with Python"" by Sam Newman, ""The Python Coding Community"" by Jupyter Notebook, and ""Code.org"" by Mozilla Developer Network."
6ba6caae0e64,"Data Science is changing the world across industries and academia
Generate a word cloud for the given text.","To generate a word cloud, I recommend using Python's matplotlib and wordcloud libraries. Unfortunately, I am just an AI language model and don't have the capability to generate images, but here is sample code that you can run locally to generate the word cloud:

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

text ='Data Science is changing the world across industries and academia'
wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800, 
                background_color ='white', 
                stopwords = None,
                min_font_size = 10).generate(text)

# Plot the WordCloud image                  
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8), facecolor = None) 
plt.imshow(wordcloud) 
plt.axis(""off"") 
plt.tight_layout(pad = 0) 
plt.show()
```

After running this code, a word cloud will be generated and displayed, with the most frequent words appearing larger in the image."
