ceb51c1991e9,Explain how I can get a series of terms which approximates the prime counting function more and more precisely,"The prime counting function, denoted by π(x), is the number of prime numbers less than or equal to x. One way to approximate π(x) is by using a series expansion. One such series is the prime number theorem, which states that π(x) is approximately equal to x/ln(x) as x approaches infinity.

Another way to approximate π(x) is by using a numerical method, such as the sieve of Eratosthenes. This method involves iterating through all the integers from 2 to x-1 and marking as composite any that have a divisor greater than x. The remaining integers are the prime numbers less than or equal to x.

You can also use the Euler-Maclaurin formula which is a closed-form series that gives the sum of the prime numbers up to a certain limit.

You can also use the Riemann Hypothesis, which is a conjecture that the nontrivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function all lie on the critical line, which is a line in the complex plane. This hypothesis can be used to make more precise estimates of π(x)

In general, the more terms you use in the series expansion, the more precise the approximation will be. However, the computational cost of using more terms also increases."
2e2f1540e68c,"Can we find a formula to generate all prime numbers, and is the distribution of primes truly random?","There are several formulas that generate all prime numbers, but they're not efficient enough to be of any practical use. For example, a formula devised by C. P. Willans in 1964 does technically return the $n$th prime, but it does so by summing $2^n$ values, each of which requires a factorial to compute. 

As for randomness, as the set of prime numbers is fixed, it can't be ""truly"" random, only pseudorandom. It's also not uniform, as evidenced by e.g. the Ulam spiral and its unnatural frequency of straight lines."
