09621f59b6d9,"What book is the following passage from?

""In the dawn there is a man progressing over the plain by means of holes which he is making in the ground. He uses an implement with two handles and he chucks it into the hole and he enkindles the stone in the hole with his steel hole by hole striking the fire out of the rock which God has put there. On the plain behind him are the wanderers in search of bones and those who do not search and they move haltingly in the light like mechanisms whose movements are monitored with escapement and pallet so that they appear restrained by a prudence or reflectiveness which has no inner reality and they cross in their progress one by one that track of holes that runs to the rim of the visible ground and which seems less the pursuit of some continuance than the verification of a principle, a validation of sequence and causality as if each round and perfect hole owed its existence to the one before it there on that prairie upon which are the bones and the gatherers of bones and those who do not gather. He strikes fire in the hole and draws out his steel. Then they all move on again.""

","The passage is from the novel ""Blood Meridian"" by Cormac McCarthy. The novel is set in the 1840s and tells the story of a group of scalp hunters who travel across the American Southwest. The passage describes one of the hunters, Glanton, as he makes his way across the plain. Glanton is a violent and ruthless man, and he is driven by a desire for blood and violence. The passage suggests that Glanton is a man who is out of step with the world around him. He is a man who is driven by his own dark desires, and he is not bound by the same rules and conventions as other people. The passage also suggests that Glanton is a man who is ultimately alone. He is surrounded by other people, but he is not truly connected to them. He is a man who is lost and searching for something, but he is not sure what that something is.

The passage is written in a very distinctive style. McCarthy uses long, complex sentences and unusual word choices. The passage is also full of imagery and symbolism. The holes that Glanton makes in the ground are symbolic of his violence and his destructiveness. The bones that are scattered across the plain are symbolic of the death and destruction that Glanton leaves in his wake. The passage is a powerful and disturbing description of a man who is lost and alone in the world."
