•He has proposed and signed into law a major $1.9 trillion COVID-19 relief stimulus package which provides $1,400 direct checks, extended unemployment benefits, and funding for vaccine distribution. His supporters believe this will help accelerate economic recovery.

•He aims to take a more traditional, centrist Democratic approach - focusing on issues like economic recovery, expanding healthcare, climate change mitigation, immigration reform, etc. His supporters believe this can help unite and heal divisions.

However, there are also some potential downsides and criticisms of his presidency so far:

•His opponents argue he is pushing a too progressive agenda and signing too many executive orders. They believe he should work more with Republicans in Congress.

•His handling of certain issues like the border crisis, trade deals, Middle East policy is criticized by some. His opponents argue his policies/approaches on these issues are misguided.

•He faces doubts given his age (78) and mental fitness. His occasional verbal gaffes and mistakes have raised concerns about his abilities from some. His opponents question whether he is up to the task physically and mentally.

•There are still many ongoing crises - the pandemic, economic turmoil, immigration issues, climate change, etc. It's unclear if his policies and leadership will be enough to adequately address these challenges.

So in summary, opinions on Biden's presidency so far tend to fall along partisan lines. His supporters believe he is restoring stability and tackling key issues, while his critics argue he is pushing a misguided agenda and face doubts about his abilities. As with any President, more time is needed to make a fair assessment."
