2. Select a programming language or development platform for building the GUI, such as Java, Python, C#, or a visual GUI builder tool.

3. Design the layout and user interface elements. This includes labels, text fields, buttons, and other components necessary for the search and data display functions.

4. Write the code or use the development tool to connect the GUI to the database. This will likely involve writing SQL queries and using a database connector to retrieve and display the data.

5. Test the search functionality and data display to ensure they are operating as intended. Make any necessary tweaks or adjustments to refine the user experience.

6. Deploy the GUI and make it available for use, either as a standalone application or as part of a larger system.

Remember, it's important to keep the user experience in mind when designing and developing a GUI. Make sure that the search and data display functions are intuitive and easy to use, while still providing the information and functionality that users need."
f63ccf55cff0,Why does the flu virus change every year?,"The influenza virus circulates widely in the human population, mutating rapidly in order to avoid immune response and immune memory against particular strains of the virus. By a process of natural selection, recent mutations that improve the virus’ survival chances tend to become more prevalent in the RNA of the virus. As such, genetic mutations and variations in antigens and surface proteins, as well as new combinations of mutations in the virus’ RNA ensure that each year the millions of flu virus particles circulating throughout the population appear to be newly “invented” for humans and their immune systems. This helps ensure that the risk of flu infections remains high every flu season, and allows the virus to quickly spread and adapt to the human immune system."
