9b4d8b0ba9eb,"    1. Why did Mr. Hyde have the key to Dr. Jekyll's House?
    2. Why did Utterson say 'Dr Jekyll would not be pleased'?
 3. What did Poole mean when he said his master was 'got rid of'?
 4. What do you think had been in the bottle next to the body of Mr Hyde?
 5. Why were Mr Hyde's clothers 'far too big for him'?
 6. After he had read the note, where did Utterson think Dr Jekyll was?
 7. How did things get out of control for Dr Jekyll?
 8. Why did Dr Jekyll say in his statement that it was ""my true hour of death'?","1. Mr. Hyde had the key to Dr. Jekyll's house because he was the alter ego of Dr. Jekyll and had access to all his possessions.
2. Utterson said 'Dr Jekyll would not be pleased' because he was worried that Dr. Jekyll's reputation would be damaged if it was discovered that he had a connection to Mr. Hyde.
3. When Poole said his master was 'got rid of', he meant that he believed Dr. Jekyll had been replaced by someone else or had been killed.
4. It is possible that the bottle next to the body of Mr. Hyde contained the potion that Dr. Jekyll used to transform into Mr. Hyde, which may have caused his death.
5. Mr. Hyde's clothes were 'far too big for him' because they were actually Dr. Jekyll's clothes, which were too large for Mr. Hyde's smaller frame.
6. After he had read the note, Utterson thought Dr. Jekyll was hiding somewhere in his laboratory or study, where he conducted his experiments.
7. Things got out of control for Dr. Jekyll because he became addicted to the thrill of transforming into Mr. Hyde and indulging in his vices, which led to him losing control of his alter ego and ultimately to his downfall.
8. Dr. Jekyll said in his statement that it was ""my true hour of death"" because he believed that his experiment and the creation of Mr. Hyde had brought about his own destruction and marked the end of his life as he knew it."
