6f5ee4c97905,can you suggest a slightly offbeat thing for a tourist to do in Shanghai today?,"Sure, here's an offbeat thing to do in Shanghai today:

Visit the Shanghai Museum of Propaganda Posters, also known as Propaganda Poster Museum. This museum is located in the heart of the city and it's a unique and interesting place to visit. It's open from 9am to 5pm, and it's located in the People's Square.

This museum is the only museum in China that focuses on propaganda posters and it's an excellent way to learn about the history of Chinese Communism and the role of propaganda in the country. The museum has a vast collection of propaganda posters from the 1920s to the 1980s, including many from the Cultural Revolution. The collection includes posters from various themes such as the revolution, the Red Army, the agricultural and industrial revolution, and the role of women in the revolution.

Visiting this museum is a great way to learn about the history of China, the role of propaganda in the country and the cultural and social changes that occurred during the Communist regime. It's a great way to get a deeper understanding of Chinese culture and history, and it's a unique experience that can't be found anywhere else in the world."
b1a6eba08476,suggest how I could make the case to my son's school that he should be assessed for extra time during exams. they have not replied to previous emails and I have a face-to-face meeting with them soon.,"Here are some suggestions for making the case for extra time during exams for your son:

• Provide specific examples of how your son's performance is impacted by time constraints. For example, does he work slowly? Does he have a hard time focusing for long periods? Does he get distracted easily? Providing concrete examples will help demonstrate the need.

• Share any medical diagnoses or learning needs that your son has that can impact his performance under time pressure. For example, ADHD, dyslexia, anxiety, etc. Offer to provide documentation from doctors or therapists. 

• Discuss how extra time is a reasonable accommodation that will allow your son to demonstrate his knowledge without being impaired by the timing. Explain that it will allow him to focus on the content, not the clock.

• Highlight your son's strengths and abilities, and explain how extra time will allow those abilities to shine through. Explain that you want him to be assessed based on his skills and knowledge, not his speed.

• Request a trial period to see if extra time makes a difference. For example, ask if he can have extra time for one exam and compare his performance and focus to other exams without extra time. Seeing concrete results can help make the case.

• Bring copies of your previous emails as evidence that you have been trying to resolve this issue for some time. Politely but firmly reiterate your concerns about the lack of response.

• You may also want to do some research on your legal rights regarding accommodations for students with learning or medical needs. Come armed with that information in case you need to make the case that assessing for extra time is legally required.

With preparation and concrete evidence, you have a good chance of making a compelling case for why your son should be assessed for extra time during exams. Be open to answering any questions they may have as well. I hope this helps and good luck!"
