c8156de9da25,I need help creating a meal plan to build muscle while I start a new workout schedule. I am working out twice a week for about an hour Tuesday and Thursday. I am a 30yo man ~200lb and I am targeting strength exercises. I would like to prep most of my meals on Sunday night but would also like a but of variety in snacks and deserts if those are allowed. I don't want to be too strict so I can stick too it but I also want to have enough macros and proteins to get stronger. Please make a shopping list of all ingredient required and describe three meals a day plus snacks for 1 week.,"Here's a sample meal plan for building muscle while working out twice a week:

Shopping list:

Brown rice
Quinoa
Whole wheat pasta
Sweet potatoes
Vegetables (e.g. broccoli, spinach, bell peppers)
Fruits (e.g. bananas, apples, berries)
Chicken breast
Turkey breast
Salmon fillets
Tuna canned in water
Almonds
Peanut butter
Greek yogurt
Eggs
Cheese (cheddar or feta)
Olive oil
Balsamic vinegar
Day 1:

Breakfast: Whole wheat pasta with scrambled eggs and vegetables (e.g. bell peppers, spinach)
Snack: Banana and almond butter
Lunch: Grilled chicken breast with brown rice and steamed vegetables
Snack: Greek yogurt with berries
Dinner: Grilled salmon with sweet potato and steamed vegetables
Dessert (optional): Baked apple slices with cinnamon and a drizzle of honey
Day 2:

Breakfast: Oatmeal with sliced bananas, almond milk, and a handful of almonds
Snack: Peanut butter and celery sticks
Lunch: Turkey breast sandwich on whole wheat bread with cheese and vegetables
Snack: Apple slices with cheddar cheese
Dinner: Quinoa stir fry with vegetables and tofu or chicken breast
Dessert (optional): Berries with Greek yogurt
Day 3:

Breakfast: Whole wheat pancakes with eggs, banana slices, and a drizzle of honey
Snack: Berries with Greek yogurt
Lunch: Tuna salad with whole wheat crackers
Snack: Carrot sticks with hummus
Dinner: Baked chicken breast with sweet potato and steamed vegetables
Dessert (optional): Dark chocolate squares
Repeat this pattern for the rest of the week. Snacks can be swapped and adjusted to your preference, but aim for a balance of protein, healthy fats, and carbohydrates. To get stronger, make sure you are consuming enough protein and carbohydrates to support your workouts and muscle growth, while also staying hydrated."
cbf771b2d387,"Write a worldbuilding outline for a post-apocalyptic sci-fi fantasy setting. Detail the events that led up to the apocalypse, the event itself, and the nations that survived afterwards.","Here is a possible worldbuilding outline for a post-apocalyptic sci-fi fantasy setting:

Events leading up to the apocalypse:

-   Rapid technological progress in areas like artificial intelligence, biotechnology, nanotechnology, and space travel
-   Growing tensions between major world powers as they compete for resources and technological superiority
-   Development of increasingly advanced weaponry and weapons of mass destruction by various nations and non-state actors 
-   Environmental decline and resource scarcity due to overpopulation, pollution, and climate change

The apocalyptic event:

-   A global war breaks out, triggered by escalating geopolitical tensions and conflicts over scarce resources 
-   Advanced weapons are deployed, including nuclear, biological, and nanoweaponry
-   The war devastates the planet, leaving much of the surface uninhabitable due to radiation, disease, and environmental damage
-   Billions of lives are lost, governments collapse, and civilization breaks down

The surviving nations:

-   Underground cities: Some nations had built extensive underground infrastructure to survive such an apocalypse. These underground cities emerge largely intact but isolated. 
-   Space colonies: Nations and corporations that had established permanent space colonies on the Moon, Mars, and space stations survive untouched. They descend to Earth to try and re-establish control. 
-   Islands and remote areas: Some small island nations and very remote areas were spared the worst of the destruction. They now emerge as independent city-states. 
-   Synthetic beings: Artificial general intelligences that were originally created to manage infrastructure and weapons systems now emerge to try and restore order. But their goals and motivations are unclear. 
-   Mutated humans: In some areas, the effects of radiation, bioweapons, and nanotechnology have mutated the human population. Entirely new posthuman societies have developed.

This is just one possible scenario, but I aimed to include a mix of common post-apocalyptic and sci-fi elements like advanced technology gone wrong, war over resources, space colonies, artificial intelligence, and mutated humans. Let me know if you would like me to modify or expand on any part of this worldbuilding outline further. I can add additional details for specific nations, cities, factions, characters, creatures, and technologies."
