4e6407929888,Is Pluto a planet?,"Yes, Pluto is a planet. It is the ninth planet from the Sun and is the largest object in the Kuiper belt, a region of the solar system beyond the orbit of Neptune. It was discovered in 1930 and was initially classified as a planet, but in 2006, it was reclassified as a dwarf planet"
bb9296695937,What should you do if you get lost on a hike?,"Hmm this is a challenging question!  In my opinion there are multiple options here, and what you should do will depend on a number of factors such as the nature of the hike, how skilled you are as a hiker, the policies of the trail organization, etc.  Here are some general tips:

-If you are only slightly off track, you should try to find a familiar landmark or subtle trail feature that will help you get back on track.  Every good woodland trail will have subtle and not-so-subtle trail features that mark the path, so use these carefully to help guide you back to the main path.
-If you are quite lost and unsure how to proceed, stay put and try to build a makeshift shelter or camp, so you will be better prepared for a long wait until rescue.  You should try to signal to any searchers that you are in the area by building some sort of large conspicuous marker.  You should ration your food supplies so that you have enough to last several days.  In winter conditions you should also build an emergency shelter and try to stay warm.  In hot conditions you should seek out shade and ration your water supplies.  If rescue is not imminent you should"
4bb57fd80373,Explain why labor unions have become less popular in the past few decades.,"Labor unions have experienced a decline in popularity over the past few decades for several reasons. Some of the contributing factors may include: 

1. Changes in the economy: With the shift from a manufacturing-based economy to a service-based economy, there has been a decrease in unionized jobs. Service sector jobs often pay less and offer fewer benefits, making it more difficult for unions to organize these workers. 

2. Globalization: Many companies have moved their operations to countries with weaker labor regulations and lower wages, making it more difficult for unions to organize workers and negotiate for better wages and working conditions. 

3. Right-to-work laws: Many states have passed right-to-work laws (laws that prohibit unions from requiring employees to join the union or pay union dues), which has weakened the power of unions and made it more difficult for them to organize workers. 

4. Anti-union sentiment: Some companies have actively discouraged and prevented union organization through tactics such as union-busting (hiring outside firms to discourage or prevent unionization) and threats of relocating or closing down operations. 

5. Perception: Some workers may view unions as irrelevant or unnecessary in the current economic climate, believing that they can negotiate better wages and working conditions on their own. There is also a perception among some workers that unions are corrupt or self-serving, which has contributed to their decline in popularity.

Overall, a combination of economic, political, and cultural factors have contributed to the decline in popularity of labor unions over the past few decades."
