829111997a1b,Which programs can I use in linux to translate a .ts file.,"There are a few options for translating .ts files in Linux:

1. Qt Linguist - This is part of the Qt framework and is a GUI tool for translating Qt .ts files. If you have Qt installed, you can run it with `linguist`.

2. gettext - The GNU gettext tools include `msgfmt` which can compile .ts files into .mo files for use in translation. You can also use `msgmerge` to update translations. These are command line tools.

3. Virtaal - This is an open source translation tool that supports .ts and other file formats. It has a GUI interface and includes features like translation memory and terminology management.

4. OmegaT - This is another open source tool for translating .ts and other files. It is Java-based so runs on Linux, Windows and Mac. It has a GUI interface and translation memory features.

5. POEdit - This is a popular open source translation editor for Linux and Windows. It supports .ts files and many other formats. It has a GUI interface with many useful features for translators.

6. Gtranslator - This is a GNOME-based translation tool for .ts and .po files. So if you use GNOME desktop environment, this may integrate well. It has a simple GUI interface.

7. Kate - If you want a simple text editor, Kate supports .ts files and has some basic features for translating and validating the files. But it lacks the more advanced features of the other tools I mentioned.

So in summary, there are many good open source options for Linux to translate .ts files, with varying levels of complexity. Let me know if you have any other questions!"
